## Cursor rule authoring (.mdc)

When writing or editing Cursor `.mdc` rule files, follow these conventions:

**`alwaysApply: true`**
Use for universal conventions that apply to every session (code style, naming, project-wide constraints).
Keep these minimal and high-signal — every always-on rule adds to every prompt.

**`globs:`**
Use for file-type-specific rules. Examples: `**/*.ts`, `src/api/**`, `**/*.test.ts`.
Omit `alwaysApply` or set it to `false` when using globs — the rule fires only on matching files.

**`description:`**
Shown in the rule picker. Write what the rule *enforces*, not just its name.
Good: `"Enforce snake_case for Python identifiers and 4-space indent"`
Avoid: `"Python rules"`

**Splitting rules**
Prefer multiple focused `.mdc` files over one large monolithic rule file.
A rule named `api-contracts.mdc` is easier to toggle and review than a 200-line catch-all.

**Scope**
- Rules under `.cursor/rules/` are **project-scoped** (checked in, shared with the team)
- Rules under `~/.cursor/rules/` are **user-global** (apply to all your projects)
